# =============================================================================
#  Generated by install.sh
# =============================================================================
#
# Machine-specific ESP-IDF paths. The repo carries env/idf_env.sh.in (the template);
# the install carries the facts. A hardcoded IDF path is correct for exactly one
# developer and broken for everybody else.
env/idf_env.sh


# =============================================================================
#  Build output
# =============================================================================
client/build/
mcu/build/

# ESP-IDF writes these: machine and board state, not source.
mcu/sdkconfig
mcu/sdkconfig.old

# Superseded by env/idf_env.sh.in + install.sh -- a personal, machine-specific
# activation script that predates the installer.
mcu/env_activate.sh


# =============================================================================
#  Doxygen output
# =============================================================================
#
# Generated documentation does not belong in version control: it is derived from
# the source, it is large, and Doxygen rewrites nearly every file on every run --
# so a one-line comment change would produce a fifty-file diff.
#
# Commit the Doxyfile, not its output. Same reasoning as a Makefile: the recipe is
# source, the binary is not. Regenerate with:  doxygen Doxyfile
#
# Named 'doxygen' rather than 'docs' because mcu/docs already exists -- two
# directories called docs would be a trap.
doxygen/


# =============================================================================
#  Vendor datasheets
# =============================================================================
#
# Espressif's, Bosch's and TI's documents. Not ours to redistribute, and they get
# revised -- a copy checked in here would go stale without saying so.
# mcu/docs/README.md links to all of them.
#
# BOTH lines below are necessary, and they cannot be collapsed into "mcu/docs/".
#
# Ignoring a DIRECTORY makes git skip it entirely: it never descends, never sees
# what is inside, and the negation below could not rescue anything because the file
# was never looked at. Git says so itself -- "It is not possible to re-include a
# file if a parent directory of that file is excluded."
#
# Ignoring the CONTENTS (the /*) leaves the directory itself visible, so git still
# walks into it -- and only then can the negation take effect.
mcu/docs/*
!mcu/docs/README.md


# =============================================================================
#  Editor litter
# =============================================================================
#
# Vim swap files are DOT-PREFIXED: editing common.h produces .common.h.swp, not
# common.h.swp. A bare *.swp does not match them, which is how two of them ended up
# in the first commit of this repo.
#
# They are binary editor state, and a swap file for a buffer with unsaved changes
# contains those changes -- so committing one can leak text that was never meant to
# be saved.
#
# The [a-p] range catches vim's rollover names: .foo.swp, then .foo.swo, .foo.swn,
# and so on backwards through the alphabet as more instances open the same file.
.*.sw[a-p]
*.sw[a-p]
*~
.#*
\#*#

# Kate / KWrite, Emacs backups, and the rest.
*.kate-swp
.idea/
.vscode/

# macOS and Windows, in case anyone clones this on one.
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db


# =============================================================================
#  Scratch
# =============================================================================
tree.txt
*Untitled*
*.log
